'''Guillem d'Areny-Plandolit''' (19 February 1822&nbsp;– 23 February 1876), was an [[Andorra]]n nobleman and politician.

== Biography ==

=== Early life ===
Guillem d'Areny-Plandolit was born on 19 February 1822 in [[La Seu d'Urgell]] in the Catalan [[Pyrenees]], close to the [[Principality of Andorra]]. He was the only son of Josep Plandolit Targarona and Maria Rosa Areny.{{sfn|Obiols|Miró|2014|p=203}}{{sfn|Albert i Corp|1988}} He belonged to one of the most prominent Catalan families at the time, with a long industrial and commercial background that traces its origins back to the 17th century.{{sfn|Codina et al.|2006|p=6}}

His mother died nine months after his birth, in September. Afterward, Josep and his son moved to Andorra, settling in [[Ordino]] where he eventually remarried. Josep died on 17 July 1843 aged 55 at the family estate after a long illness.{{sfn|Bacquer|1998}}

In 1841, at the age of 19, Areny-Plandolit married Maria Dolors Parella, Baroness of Senaller.{{sfn|Miró i Solà|2016|loc=''Segle XIX''}} They had seven children, five of whom survived to adulthood.{{sfn|Bacquer|1998}} 

=== Wife's murder ===
Tragedy struck on 19 June 1855, when his first wife was murdered at the age of 30 in [[Barcelona]], where the family had property they frequently visited. Her attacker, Blas Durana Atauri, stabbed her 13 times in a carefully premeditated attack.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=627}} The crime became well-known in 19th-century Barcelona and shocked the public at the time because of the status and personality of those involved and also for its bizarre aftermath.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=632}}{{sfn|Theros|2012|loc=''El País''}}

Durana was an infantry colonel in the [[Spanish Army]] and was stationed in Barcelona at the time. He frequently attended social gatherings where he attempted to climb the social ladder and court women. He soon caught wind of the Baroness and fell deeply in love with her. Parella initially welcomed and tolerated his compliments, but became alarmed when Durana began appearing at an increasing amount of the same gatherings, apparently not letting up.{{sfn|Olmos|2015|loc=''El Correo''}} 

[[File:Guillem d'Areny-Plandolit 02.png|thumb|left|upright=1|Areny-Plandolit in 1866]]
After complaining to her husband, Areny-Plandolit was annoyed enough to ask his friend, [[Captain General of Catalonia]] Juan Zapatero y Navas, for help. Zapatero agreed to redeploy Durana to [[Lugo]] in [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] to mend the situation.{{sfn|Miró i Solà|2016|loc=''Segle XIX''}} Durana was able to continue his amorous siege by making up excuses and taking advantage of every opportunity to return to Barcelona, apparently still motivated by love. Fueled by frustration and envy, this feeling eventually turned into hatred. Desperate and embittered, he decided to kill Parella.{{sfn|Theros|2012|loc=''El País''}}

Durana had spent the day of the attack carefully observing the Areny-Plandolit and Parella property, hiding in an alleyway on the opposite street. He attacked the Baroness at dusk when she finally came out of the house in order to visit a theater; she died within twenty minutes.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=628}} As he did not attempt to flee, he was quickly captured by a local militia to whom he quickly identified himself and triumphantly admitted his crime.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=628}} 

Durana's lawyer tried to argue that mental instability was to blame and referred to past incidents to prove this claim.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=631}} However, he was quickly convicted and sentenced to be executed by garrotte.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=629}} Although Durana remained calm and composed during the sentencing, the method of execution came unexpectedly since he had expected to be put in front of a firing squad, something more befitting a colonel. His request to change the method of execution was denied.{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=632}}{{sfn|Pallarès-Personat|2007}}

Durana committed suicide on the eve of the execution by means of [[Mercury(II) cyanide|mercuric cyanide]], likely smuggled in by an army comrade on an earlier visit to him in prison.{{sfn|Miró i Solà|2016|loc=''Segle XIX''}}{{sfn|Blanche|1862|pp=633–635}} Rumors had been going around that the trial had been a farce and that the colonel, as a result of his rank, would somehow be allowed to escape his fate. As a result, a large crowd had gathered on the morning of the execution to witness the event. To avoid a riot, authorities wheeled out his dead body and went through the motions of the execution; essentially executing his corpse.{{sfn|Theros|2012|loc=''El País''}}{{sfn|Blanche|1862|p=634}}{{sfn|Bofarull i Terrades|2002}}

Areny-Plandolit was not present at the burial of his first wife and appears not to have mourned for long, if at all.{{sfn|Miró i Solà|2016|loc=''Segle XIX''}} He remarried a little more than three months later, to Carolina de Plandolit, his cousin.{{sfn|Pérez|2017|loc=''Taxidermidades''}} They had ten children.{{sfn|Bacquer|1998}}

=== New Reform ===
{{seealso|Andorra#19th century: the New Reform and the Andorran Question{{!}}New Reform and the Andorran Question}}
Andorra in the mid-19th century was a country in an economic crisis. Areny-Plandolit led the [[reforms]] to replace the aristocratic and [[oligarchy|oligarchical]] that previously ruled the state. The political system was largely governed based on the privileges of a small social group formed of traditional wealthy Andorran families, to whom his family also belonged. This type of oligarchical governance made it possible for them to control all the decisions made by the [[General Council (Andorra)|General Council of the Valleys]], and to manage public resources as they pleased.{{sfn|Armengol Aleix|2009|pp=178–179}}

With a total estimated population of only 4,000 residents, whose economic power was growing and eventually even surpassing that of the original wealthy families, more and more voices were demanding social and political changes. The General Council reacted with a steady refusal and inaction. This led to a group of reformists led by Areny-Plandolit to organize meetings in order to discuss the best way to bring about reform.{{sfn|Peruga Guerrero|1998}}

[[File:Pla de la Nova Reforma d'Andorra.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A picture of the Plan of the New Reform of Andorra in a glass box in a museum|Plan of the New Reform of Andorra]]
On 22 April 1866, The New Reform ({{lang-ca|Nova Reforma}}) was decreed by the Episcopal [[Co-Princes of Andorra|Co-Prince]], Bishop [[Josep Caixal i Estradé]], and established the basis of the [[Constitution of Andorra|Andorran constitution]] and symbols (such as the [[Flag of Andorra|tricolor flag]]) of Andorra. It was ratified three years later by [[Napoleon&nbsp;III]].{{sfn|Pons|2018|loc=''El Nacional''}}

The reforms had several effects. Most importantly, it gave every citizen of the country the right to vote. It also promised regular elections; in this case twelve of the twenty-four councilors were to be elected every two years, with a maximum post length of four years. There was also the creation of the position of town commissioner in order to control public spending and put a halt to the waste of resources.{{sfn|Albert i Corp|1988}}

After producing the official document listing the reforms in May 1866, Areny-Plandolit was elected [[List of First Syndics of the General Council|First Syndic]] of the General Council, a position akin to [[Speaker (politics)|speaker]].{{sfn|Albert i Corp|1988}}{{sfn|Armengol Aleix|2009|pp=345–347}}

{{Quote|text = To name the authorities constituting the Common, all the voters of each parish shall have a right to vote. To name the four members of the General Council, all of the voters of each parish shall also have the right to vote.{{sfn|d'Areny-Plandolit|1866}} |title = Excerpt from the Plan of the New Reform}}

